@index "CanDo_MasterIndex"

@node "CanDo_Window_Editor" "CanDo's Window Editor"
@toc "CanDo_Main"
The Window Editor Requester allows you to define the kind of window to
open, what dimensions it should have, its Attributes, and what scripts will
be performed when possible Window Events occur.
__________________________________________________________________________

@{fg highlight}Window Title@{fg text}

   Title  [Unnamed...     ]

   The Window Title field sets the text which will appear in the
   window's title bar.

   Clearing this field will remove the text.  However, to keep your
   window from having a title bar you must also disable the Close
   Button, Depth Button, and Drag bar.  See: @{" Objects " link "CDR_Window_Objects"}.
__________________________________________________________________________

@{fg highlight}Where to open the window@{fg text}
   Open the window onto...
       [x] @{" our own private screen.                   " link "CDR_Window_PrivateScreen"}
       [ ] @{" the Workbench screen.                     " link "CDR_Window_WorkbenchScreen"}
       [ ] @{" a Public Screen.  [Undefined Screen Name] " link "CDR_Window_PublicScreen"}
       [ ] @{" the current screen.                       " link "CDR_Window_CurrentScreen"}

   These options control, or in some cases suggest, where the window
   will be opened.
__________________________________________________________________________

@{fg highlight}Window Dimensions@{fg text}
   @{" Origin  X[0    ]  Y[0    ] " link "CDR_Window_Origin"}

   [x] @{" Normal Window        " link "CDR_Window_NormalWindow"}
         @{" Available Modes... " link "CDR_Window_AvailableModes"}
         @{" W[320  ]  H[200  ] " link "CDR_Window_Size"}
         @{" Colors    16       " link "CDR_Window_ColorDisplay"}
         @{" ModeID  0x00000000 " link "CDR_Window_DisplayMode"}, shown when ExpertMode is on.
          
   [ ] @{" Picture Window       " link "CDR_Window_PictureWindow"}
           [ @{fg shadow}Undefined Image@{fg text}    ]
_________________________________________________________________________

@{fg highlight}Window Attributes@{fg text}

   Attributes...
   @{" Objects " link "CDR_Window_Objects"} @{" Options " link "CDR_Window_Options"} @{" Colors " link "CDR_Window_Colors"}
__________________________________________________________________________

@{fg highlight}Window Scripts@{fg text}

   @{" Scripts... " link "CDR_Window_Scripts"}
   
   Close Button, Resized, Activated, Deactivated and AppEvent

@endnode

@node "CDR_Window_PrivateScreen" "Window Editor's Private Screen mode"
@toc "CanDo_Window_Editor"
@{fg highlight}Open the window onto our own private screen...@{fg text}

   This is the default selection.  The Window Dimensions part of this
requester lets you specify the kind of screen to open.

@endnode

@node "CDR_Window_WorkbenchScreen" "Window Editor's Workbench Screen mode"
@toc "CanDo_Window_Editor"
@{fg highlight}Open the window onto the Workbench screen...@{fg text}

   This selection suggests that the window be opened on the Workbench
screen.  If the information you specify in the Window Dimensions is
incompatible with the current Workbench screen, CanDo will open your window
on a Private Screen which supports the Window Dimensions you specified.

   Your Window Dimensions will be incompatible with the Workbench screen if
it requires more colors than the Workbench, or if its dimensions are larger
than the Workbench's dimensions.  For example, if you request 8 colors and
the current Workbench has only 4 colors, CanDo will open a private screen.

@endnode

@node "CDR_Window_PublicScreen" "Window Editor's Public Screen mode"
@toc "CanDo_Window_Editor"
@{fg highlight}Open the window onto a Public Screen...@{fg text}

   Selecting this option tells CanDo to open the window on an existing
Public Screen.  Basically, a Public Screen is a screen opened and made
publicly available by an application.  When it does this, it gives the
screen a Public name.  Other applications, such as your CanDo Deck, can use
this name to open a window on the Public screen as a visitor.  Workbench,
for example, is a Public Screen that applications can open on.

   You can make your application open on a Public Screen if it is
available.  Many of the newer products, especially ones with ARexx support,
provide Public Screens.  Consult the products's documentation for the
Public name.  Or, you can use the PublicScreen requester, described below,
to find the name.

   When you click on the Public Screen Name button, which initially
displays the default text "@{fg highlight}Undefined Screen Name@{fg text}", the PublicScreen
requester will appear.  This requester will display the names of all Public
Screens which are currently opened.  Double-clicking an entry will select
it and return to the Window Editor.  If the name is not currently
available, you can specify it by typing it into the text field located at
the bottom of the requester.

   When you specify a Public Screen that is not available when your
application tries to open the window, CanDo will open your window on
Workbench.

   Specifying a Public Screen may overide many of the Window Dimensions
settings.  For example, if you specify 32 colors and the Public Screen only
has 8 colors, your window will open on it; however, your window will
only display 8 colors.  You can use this option to specify "Workbench" and
your window will open on the Workbench, even if the colors are incompatible
or the dimensions are larger than the Workbench screen.

@endnode

@node "CDR_Window_CurrentScreen" "Window Editor's Current Screen mode"
@toc "CanDo_Window_Editor"
@{fg highlight}Open the window onto the current screen...@{fg text}

   This option is used for Sub-Deck windows allowing your window to open on
the same screen as the Parent Deck.

@endnode

@node "CDR_Window_Origin" "Window Editor's Origin"
@toc "CanDo_Window_Editor"
@{fg highlight}Origin  X[0    ]  Y[0    ]@{fg text}

   The X and Y values designate the initial position of the Window.  Most
applications use the default values of 0.

   The X value is only used when the Window is opened on Workbench or some
other Public Screen, or when used as a Sub-Deck window.  It indicates the
initial horizontal position of the Window.

   The Y value indicates the initial vertical position.  If the window is
opened as it's own Private Screen, it will indicate the vertical position
of the new screen.  If it is opened on another screen, it indicates the
vertical position of the window on the screen.

@endnode

@node "CDR_Window_NormalWindow" "Window Editor's Normal Window"
@toc "CanDo_Window_Editor"
@{fg highlight}Normal Window flag@{fg text}

   You can select between Normal Window and @{" Picture Window " link "CDR_Window_PictureWindow"}.  A Normal
Window uses the @{" Available Modes " link "CDR_Window_AvailableModes"} requester to specify the window mode and
colors.

   A checkmark next to "Normal Window" indicates it is enabled.

@endnode

@node "CDR_Window_PictureWindow" "Window Editor's Picture Window"
@toc "CanDo_Window_Editor"
@{fg highlight}Picture Window flag and button@{fg text}

   You can select either @{" Normal Window " link "CDR_Window_NormalWindow"} or Picture Window.  In picture
window mode you can define an image to be used as the backdrop of your
window.  The window's size will be based on the image's size.  Note that,
due to color palette and screen resolution differences, the image may look
strange unless the @{" Private Screen " link "CDR_Window_PrivateScreen"} flag is turned on.

   To define an image simply click on the button below the Picture Window
flag.  A file requester will appear to help you in your selection of an
image.

@endnode

@node "CDR_Window_AvailableModes" "Window Editor's Available Modes"
@toc "CanDo_Window_Editor"
   This button brings up a requester allowing you to select from the
Display Modes which are available on your Amiga.  Remember, the modes
available on your system may not be the same ones available on someone
else's computer.  If you distribute your deck and the selected mode is not
available on the computer that is running, CanDo will attempt to use
standard OS calls to convert the selected mode to the best one available.

   The selected entry is highlighted in the list.  The available colors are
indicated in the list on the right side of the requester.  You can also
edit the origin, @{" X and Y " link "CDR_Window_Origin"}, and size, @{" H and W " link "CDR_Window_Size"}, for the window.  These
values are the same ones which appear on the Window Editor.  When you
select "Ok", these values will be displayed in the Window Editor.  However,
you must use this requester to change the number of colors.

   You can also select the Overscan size by selecting one of the entries in
the Overscan Menu.  The available sizes are Nominal, Text, Graphic and
Maximum.  The Overscan sizes used on your system are indicated and set
using the Amiga Overscan Preferences.

@endnode

@node "CDR_Window_Size" "Window Editor's Size"
@toc "CanDo_Window_Editor"
@{fg highlight}W[320  ]    H[200  ]@{fg text}

   These fields allow you to specify the width and height of the window.
If your window is not opening on another screen (i.e.  Workbench), then
these values define the width and height of the screen to be opened.

@endnode

@node "CDR_Window_ColorDisplay" "Window Editor's Colors"
@toc "CanDo_Window_Editor"
@{fg highlight}Colors      16      @{fg text}

   The Window Editor contains a read only area which displays the number of
colors to be used on your window.  To change this value, click on the
@{" Available Modes " link "CDR_Window_AvailableModes"} button.

@endnode

@node "CDR_Window_DisplayMode" "Window Editor's ModeID"
@toc "CanDo_Window_Editor"
@{fg highlight}ModeID    0x00000000@{fg text}

   This read only field is visible only when ExpertMode is turned on.  The
field shows the best display ModeID given the width, height and colors.
This field also appears on the @{" Available Modes " link "CDR_Window_AvailableModes"} requester.

@endnode

@node "CDR_Window_Objects" "Window Editor's Objects"
@toc "CanDo_Window_Editor"
   The Window Editor Objects Requester lets you choose the Amiga supported
window objects to put on your window.

   [x] Close Button
   [ ] Depth Button
   [ ] Drag Bar
   [ ] Size Button
   [x] Visible Borders

   Clicking on the box next to the title toggles a checkmark which
indicates if the object is to be used.
__________________________________________________________________________

@{fg highlight}Close Button@{fg text}

   The Close Button is the box in the upper left corner of a Window which
the user can click on to close the window.  This button is commonly seen on
many Amiga windows including the windows opened by Workbench.

   Your CanDo window is not automatically closed when the user clicks on
the close button.  You must create a @{" Close Button Script " link "CDR_Window_Scripts"} which tells
CanDo what to do when the Close button is selected.
__________________________________________________________________________

@{fg highlight}Depth Button@{fg text}

   The Depth Button appears in the upper right corner of your window.  It
allows the user of your application to push your window to the front or to
the back of other windows on the screen.
__________________________________________________________________________

@{fg highlight}Drag Bar@{fg text}

   The Drag Bar option allows the user of your application to use the
window title bar to drag the window to different part of the screen.
__________________________________________________________________________

@{fg highlight}Size Button@{fg text}

   The Size button is located in the lower right corner of your window.  It
allows the user to resize the window.  You may want to create a @{" Resized " link "CDR_Window_Scripts"}
script which will be performed whenever the user resizes the window.

   You might use the @{" SetWindowLimits " link "CanDo_SetWindowLimits"} command in the Card's
@{" AfterAttachment " link "CanDo_Card_Editor"} script to define the limits within which your window can
be resized.
__________________________________________________________________________

@{fg highlight}Visible Borders@{fg text}

   The Visible Borders function creates standard window borders around your
window.

@endnode

@node "CDR_Window_Options" "Window Editor's Options"
@toc "CanDo_Window_Editor"
   You can choose from the following options:

   [x] After opening, bring window and its screen to front
   [x] After opening, activate the window
   [ ] Open the window in BackDrop mode

   Clicking on the box next to the title toggles a checkmark which
indicates if the option is to be used.
__________________________________________________________________________

@{fg highlight}After opening, bring window and its screen to front@{fg text}

   This option automatically brings the screen on which the window is
opened to the front.  If you are going to change the colors or perform
other kinds of drawing in the AfterAttachment script of the card, you may
want to disable this option and perform a @{" ScreenTo Front " link "CanDo_ScreenTo"} command when
your drawing commands are complete.
__________________________________________________________________________

@{fg highlight}After opening, activate the window@{fg text}

   This option automatically activates the window when it is opened.

   The Amiga can have only one active window at a time.  The active window
receives keyboard input and its menus are available for use.  The Window
Activate option allows you to control whether or not your Window is the
Active Window when it is first opened.

   Most of the time you will want it to be Active.  However, there are
times when you may not.  For example, you may wish to make a CanDo
application that is started from a CLI and has a Status Window on
Workbench.  If you want to be able to continue typing in the CLI without
reactivating it, then you do not want your CanDo Window to become Active.
__________________________________________________________________________

@{fg highlight}Open the window in BackDrop mode@{fg text}

   This option causes your window to open as an Amiga BackDrop Window.

   A backdrop Window means the Window is opened behind all other windows,
but in front of other backdrop windows.  The window will not have a Window
Title and none of the Window @{" Objects " link "CDR_Window_Objects"} will be attached.  If this is a
Workbench Window, the window cannot be positioned on top of other windows,
nor can it be moved around.  When the Window is opened on a Private Screen,
you will have access to the Screen Title Bar allowing the Screen to be
lowered using the Mouse.

@endnode

@node "CDR_Window_Colors" "Window Editor's Colors"
@toc "CanDo_Window_Editor"
   Clicking the "Colors" button on the Window Editor brings up a requester
allowing you to specify the colors used for the Window's Background, Border
and Text.

   Background Color [0 ]
       Border Color [1 ]
         Text Color [0 ]
__________________________________________________________________________

@{fg highlight}Background Color@{fg text}

   This is the initial color of the Window.  If you specify a Picture
window, this value will not be used.
__________________________________________________________________________

@{fg highlight}Broder Color@{fg text}

   This is the color for drawing the Window's border and Title Bar.  If the
Window does not have a border or a Title Bar (see @{" Options " link "CDR_Window_Options"}), this value
will not be used.
__________________________________________________________________________

@{fg highlight}Text Color@{fg text}

This color is used for the Window's Title.

@endnode

@node "CDR_Window_Scripts" "Window Editor's Scripts"
@toc "CanDo_Window_Editor"
@{fg highlight}Close Button@{fg text}

   This script is performed when the Close Button, located in the upper
right corner of the window, is clicked on.

   You must have enabled the @{" Close Button Object " link "CDR_Window_Objects"} for your window.
__________________________________________________________________________

@{fg highlight}Resized@{fg text}

   When the Window is resized, you may need to redraw your Window.
Buttons, Fields, Proportional, and Memos/Lists are redrawn automatically;
however, all other imagery is not.  This script can contain commands to
redraw the imagery in the Window when it is resized.

   You must have enabled the @{" Sizeable " link "CDR_Window_Objects"} flag for your window.
__________________________________________________________________________

@{fg highlight}Activated@{fg text}

   When a user re-activates the Window, this script is performed.
__________________________________________________________________________

@{fg highlight}Deactivated@{fg text}

   When your Window is Active, and the user clicks in any other window,
your window is deactivated.  This script is performed when this happens.
__________________________________________________________________________

@{fg highlight}AppEvent@{fg text}

The AppEvent script is performed whenever a Workbench icon is dragged over
your application's window and released.  This allows you to make an
application residing on WorkBench which is notified when the user drops an
Icon on the window.

@endnode

